.<br /><br />Hmm. Trying to answer this myself by looking at the code. And I just<br />realized that I described things wrong ("spin_contended()" rather than<br />"spin_is_locked()"). So that was a bug in my description.<br /><br />One difference is that by avoiding the counter, the "do we have<br />waiters" is two values rather than one ("is spin locked" + "node list<br />head is empty"). So there are possible memory ordering issues wrt<br />reading those two fields, but I don't see it mattering: since you'd<br />need to read both "not locked" _and_ "list empty", any re-ordering<br />that shows both of those cases should be able to show the "waiters ==<br />0" case in the explicit separate counter model.<br /><br />I don't know why I care, though. For some reason that extra counter<br />just makes me go "I'm convinced it's not needed", even though I can't<br />really explain why I should care about it.<br /><br />        Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
